bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Student life office is now a part of Student and Academic Support Services (SASS).

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include Sigma XI membership nominations, meeting minutes, constitution and by-laws, annual reports, and history of Sigma Xi; student activities rosters and regulations, guides to student organizations, student telephone directory, debate team trophies, publications, photocopies of news clippings of GW Band, button, posters, academic evaluations. The collection covers the years 1915 to 2004.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into 32 series: Photographs, Posters, GW Blitz newspaper, Rock Creek magazine, Unfiltered newspaper, Office files, T-shirt, Student handbooks, Student telephone directory, Student telephone directory, Debate teama trophies, GW Journal newspaper, Ghost magazine, GW Forum magazine, GW Insider, Ex Nihilo magazine, Academic evaluations, Independence magazine, Connection newsletter, Sigma Xi records, Student activities, Sigma Xi records, Hillel, GW Band, Buttons, Posters, Sigma Xi banners, Phi Beta Kappa, Campus posters, Sigma Nu Delta Pi Chapter fraternity records, and two of Office files. Note: There are no series with numbers 11 or 25.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The mission of Hillel is to create a place to further the cultural, social and educational life of Jewish students on campus. Programs have always been diverse, ranging from the secular to the religious. Social activism and Zionism have been a vital part of Jewish campus life at George Washington University since the Menorah Society was established on November 26, 1915 as an organization of Jewish students who studied the ideals and cultures of the Jewish people. The Society's most important legacy was the formation of the Department of Semetics and the courese in Hebrew that soon followed.

The Menorah Society cotinued until the mid-1930s and by that time anotehr Jewish organization had been established on campus. The Avukah Society, or simply Avukah, was the local branch of the Student Zionist Federation. It appears as though the group was formed in mind-1920s and lasted until 1930. Then Avukah reappeared in the mid-1930s and lasted until the 1941-1942 academic year, thus being the only Jewish organization on campus during that time. There is no record of a Jewish organization for a few years until the B'nai B'rith Hillel Foundation began in 1946 with the assistance of the local Jewish community and the Hillel Councilship that had been launched two years prior in 1944. B'nai B'rith traditionally sponosored the Hillel Councilship and Hillel Foundation, however, that long relationship ended in 1995 when Hillel began the Foundation for Jewish Campus Life.

The first three decades of Jewish campus actvity follwing the B'nai B'rith Hillel Foundation's conception in 1946 was centered in an F street row house, affectionately called "Hillel House." The members remember it as dirty and cluttered, but nonetheless it was their haven. The biggest event onf Hille's first year was the Ball of Fire Dance that was open to the entire university. Among the highlights of the dance was the picking of the "Apollo" from all the male contestants. Its intitial success was so popular that it became an annual tradition until the early 1960xs. Religious observances, educational programs and social activities marked the years at the house on F street under the leadership of Rabbi Aaron B. Seidman (Director from 1951-1979). Rabbi Gerald Serotta became Director of Hillel in 1982 and it was under his leadership that Hillel finally recieved a much-needed permanent and more suitable home.

After forty years of relocation to such location as a church building and an office space, Hillel finally found an enduring home on the corner of 23rd and H streets. The site was dedicated on September 14, 1986, in honor of Lester Poretsky and marked the first permanent Hillel House in the District of Columbia. Lelia Imas and Juan Gruner of Imas Gruner A.I.A. and Associates designed the new three level 13,000 square foot structure, which includced a kosher kitchen. The Hillel House officially opened April 17, 1988 and was renamed the Gewirz Center after the late Morris Gewirz, president of the Washington B'nai B'rith Hillel Board of Governors.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of the Hillel student organization and includes correspondence, publications, photos, slides, etc. It is organized into the following sub-series: Administration, Alumni Lists, Buildings, Clippings, Correspondence, Exhibit Paper Material, General Information, Publications, Photographs, Exhibit Photographs, Slides, Scrapbook(s) and Artifacts. The materials range in date from 1949-99.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains bulletins, memorandums, and rules. They range in date from 1951 to 1971. The materials concern regulations for student activities; registration and recognition of student organizations; and demonstration, rally, and assembly guidelines.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The first box in this series contains Omicron Delta Kappa by-laws, minutes, applications, photos, reports, correspondence. They range in date from 1939-65.

The second box contains a record book of members, minutes, finances, etc. 1929-1954, 1973; record book of initiation attendees and initiates,1982-2012; 80th anniversary recognition, 2009; initiation ceremony script, 2011-2012; flag, T-shirt and pins, circa 2012.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Omicron Delta Kappa is a National leadership honor society for college students, faculty, staff, administrators, and alumni, and was chartered at George Washington University in 1929. The GW group is called the Alpha Delta Circle.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The contents of Box 2 of this series were transferred to the archives by the Office of Student Engagement in 2017 (Accession 2017-045).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains five electronic documents. These documents tell a very small portion of the history of the Sigma Nu Delta Pi Chapter fraternity at GWU. There is a spreadsheet with financial data for a crispy creme fundraiser in 2006 and a document to review and revise the pledge procedure for the fraternity and formalize a brotherhood retreat.
Although these documents do not reveal much history of the fraternity it is hopeful that more material will be donated in the future.
